text: One major issue with quite a few of these is that it has to be cooked over very high heat, and a lot of us students live in student housing with shitty fans and overly sensitive fire alarms, so we cannot cook anything over very high heat in fear of getting a fine. In my student housing, if you set of the fire alarm on a false alarm and can't get the smoke out in 10 minutes so the system can reset, you get fined $1900 (yes, it's insanely expensive and double what we get a month with our student loans). And thus, every recipe that requires something to be cooked over very high heat/seared isn't accessible for a whole lot of students

text: It is nice josh that you gave Izzy the rice cooker but you don't need to have a rice cooker to make rice. Look I'm not trying to make fun of anyone but the only thing you need is a sauce pan with a lid, I've have a small one that can only cook up to 2 cups of rice at a time. It's not hard to do remember two cups water to one cup rice. Take two cups water boil it. Next take one cup of rice, stir it up and put the lid on it, turn down the stove to low heat which with this old not so good stove for me is two. Set the timer for twenty minutes and walk away. Come back after it beeps and take off the lid and mix the rice which is fluffing up the rice. Your done turn off the stove, your done. I think it's funny that people think that they need all of this technology to cook today when back then they didn't have any of it but they still cooked even if it's basic. Plus Izzy doesn't need a over $200 coffee maker basic works as good. It is funny because my dad had one pretty close to it Cuisinart was the brand and after two years it was done I mean a alsome one with a built in coffee grinder, just because it cost more doesn't always mean it better that's all.

As once a russian uni student, I am laughing with tears on these conditionsüòÇ

 2 kitchens for a 100 people on the floor (2 stoves, 8 plaques, usually only1 stove and around 4 plaques were working, all in horrible conditions)
The life and cooking were very different then

text:
One I want to share that I know probably everyone knows, but posting in case someone doesn't know. 
With any top ramen, you can turn it into a stir fry. Just boil it like you normally would (I leave it a little firmer than usual), drain the water (assuming you boiled it in a wok), add any cooking oil, toss around, add some soy sauce and your favorite seasoning, maybe some veggies, an egg or two, and just stir fry until cooked to your liking! You can even use the seasoning packet for the soup (although lightly, it is very salty)

text:
"We didn't use a wok. I know that it's wrong."   I wish this advice would die.  (And most of Uncle Roger's criticisms with it.  He's a comedian."  

Wok on a normal Stove? Completely wasteful, and not good.  Have a giant fire?  Yeah Wok away.  Want to do a stir fry at a grill. Pan, ripping hot will beat a wok almost every day of the week. 

It just pisses me off when people continue to repeat that, because the way you did it is perfectly fine/better than with an actual wok.   

If you want to learn how to cook, listen to a chef, if you want comedy, go listen to Uncle Roger, but then forget his "Advice" and go learn from a skilled individual.

(There are flat bottom woks that are better, but still better to learn how to use a skillet especially as a college student or someone who doesn't use a wok every day.  It's perfectly fine)

text:
Something that I recommend for anyone living by themselves who want to make easy meals 5 times a weak; learn how to turn a classic vegetable based sauce into a yogurt sauce and make the yogurt yourself. Which is to say; buy a type of milk that you're not allergic to (look up 'will it yogurt' if you want vegetarian options), heat it to 82¬∞C for 30 minutes for a thick consistency, then add your sauce ingredients (preferably oven roasted for veggies) and a yogurt culture of choice and optionally 2% salt. Incubate it for 2 days for the probiotics. Pulse to desired consistency.

Slap that sauce on a plate, cook pasta, put cooked pasta on top and now you have a probiotic meal that you can prepare in the time it takes to cook pasta and it lasts for about a week or two.

I regularly make a yogurt sauce with fresh basil, fresh mint, black pepper, garlic, onion and spinach, fermented in goatmilk yogurt. But you can use it for different sauces as well.

Sadly going through that first year course also made it so I didn't further my culinary arts schooling which I do regret. text:
Well, no. Traditional foods are oftentimes very complicated. Fine dining French Cuisine is quite literally traditional French cooking. That's why it has its fingers in everybody else remotely western's cuisine. They were the first to have a true culinary tradition, and they were meticulous about writing it down in a pedagogical way.

Calling this a Torrija is also a pretty huge stretch. His obvious recipe source was combining a french toast with a churro, but more importantly, the technique is different (torrijas are are soaked in a milk and then dipped in egg, not soaked in a custard) and it's missing key ingredients (zest). Obviously I'm being picky and I'm sure there are many Spanish grandmas who make them more Josh style, but you need to be picky when you're trying to claim such a simple, widespread idea as being definitively yours. Every culture that eats bread has a similar dish.
author: @Mezmorizorz

text: ¬†@Mezmorizorz¬† on the contrary, for the most traditional foods involve very cheap and simple meals prepared with care, because they were for people with limited means (see for example stew and such). And no, clearly you have 0 idea about what Churros are in Spain sorry, you are very ignorant too.

text:
‚Äã¬†@icecreamman2687¬†I like adding "for me" at the end of subjective statements to avoid confusion or to avoid making it sound like hasty generalisation.  Sometimes statements like that can give off the impression "there's no way it could be fun, it isn't fun at all".  Same thing with it being time-consuming--you get quicker with time and practice.  Just like in academic writing, you have to practise caution, because people tend to dislike those who are overly negative or opinionated.  Even in the internet it's important to be clear and polite so that you can have your opinion heard while avoiding confusion or conflict

And I'm sayin this from experience, man.  I try to lessen my opinionated statements and in generalising things because I want to clarify it and make sure people don't get the wrong idea, which is time-consuming for both sides.  It's better to sound more open to discussion

Like if I want a smothered steak I have to cook off the toppings, clear the pan for the steak,  cook it then rest the steak and bring the toppings back into the pan to deglaze and make a sauce, etc.  1 pan recipes are nothing new of course but you can learn a lot by doing stuff that isn't normally considered 1 pan

These aren‚Äôt quick and easy at all.

 He should‚Äôve used frozen pre cut potatoes for the hash brown recipe, and use a ziploc bag to soak them in the butter. 

How many college kids have the equipment and skills to peel fresh potatoes and cut them into matchsticks? How many have cookware that can go from the stove straight into the oven?

And then there‚Äôs the cleaning.  You‚Äôve got to clean a vegetable peeler, a mandolin, a cutting board, a knife, a towel, a mixing bowl, a pan and a lid. All that for one or two servings of hash browns. 

I hate to be so negative, but it‚Äôs kind ridiculous considering the whole premise of the video is cheap and easy meals for college students. I‚Äôd like to see the college students in the video actually try to make these dishes in their kitchens.

text: Protip for other broke motherfuckers like me: try to always keep some basic building blocks in your freezer and fridge. Even just a bit of chicken and some store-bought hokkien noodles - all you need is to slice up some bell pepper, carrot and ginger, and stirfry the lot in some soy sauce and mirin and you've got a perfectly decent meal in under 10 minutes. It's not "authentic" or "restaurant grade" but it's easy and cheap and it will fill you up.
author: @ChristopherHallett

text:
Simple teriyaki rice (sorry to actual cooks for the microwave) 

Rice - use a rice cooker or follow instructions for stove top; or you could make it in a microwave: 

In a microwave safe dish (taller is better if you don't want it boiling over and then you have to clean up), add 1-2 cups of rice. Rinse the rice. Add hot water until its about an inch above the rice. Microwave full power for 10 minutes. Will likely need to add more water here, but not as much as first time. Microwave at 50% power for 15 minutes. 

Teriyaki sauce:
In a small pot or saucepan, add 1 cup water, ¬º cup soy sauce, 5 teaspoons packed brown sugar, 1 tablespoon honey (or more to taste), ¬º teaspoon garlic powder, and ¬Ω teaspoon ground ginger (I've made it without this before and it tastes just fine). Cook over medium heat until it's all melted and mixed together (about 1 minute). 

Add ¬º cup cold water and 2 tablespoons cornstarch together in a cup. Mix well (iluntil dissolved) before adding to saucepan with rest of the ingredients. Cook and stir until sauce thickens, about 5-7 minutes. It's really obvious when it thickens btw. 

Add ons:
Toss in some veggies; I like broccoli (even just frozen broccoli heated in the microwave). If going with fresh veggies, I recommend cooking them in a wok or pan first until tender.

text:
Former campus safety here. I know, I know, but this is about not waking up the rest of your residence hall at 3am.

If you live in a college dorm and you're considering recipes that involve high heat, especially the ones that need oil near smoking point:
1. Be careful. Burn ouch. Hospital expensive.
2. If your dorm does not allow indoor vaping, odds are the smoke detectors are incredibly sensitive, and throwing down too hard in the kitchen might make everyone in the building very mad if the alarms go off.

I only offer this caution because for nearly six years, at least once a year, someone in an upperclassmen building would set off a fire alarm because they did not add water to Kraft Easy Mac before microwaving.

text:
I lived in dorms all the way through college, with that ‚ÄúOne kitchen for 150 students‚Äù, and cooked a LOT:
Homemade bread, chicken picatta with mashed potatoes, pizza from scratch, spaghetti & meatballs, Steak Diane, French toast, cakes, meringue, etc.

All my equipment fit in one dishpan, and I stored it in my room. Everything was cooked in my one cast iron skillet & medium pot, or baked on my one baking sheet.

You really don‚Äôt need a lot of equipment to cook most food - certain pieces of equipment make things a little easier (I finally bought a small hand mixer after whipping egg whites with a whisk until my arm was numb!), but you really don‚Äôt need much - cutting board, a good chef‚Äôs knife, veggie peeler, paring knife, a solid French rolling pin (my sister used a wine bottle during her freshman year until she got a rolling pin for Christmas!), measuring cups/spoons, a good whisk, small & large mixing bowl, cast iron skillet, medium pot, rimmed baking sheet, a wooden spoon, a metal spatula, and a rubber spatula. That‚Äôs really all the equipment I had until several years after college.

My dad taught us how to make bread & homemade pasta with just a bowl, spoon, and baking sheet (bread) or pot to boil water (pasta).

Let me as a college student give you a vegetarian indian recipe ....

1- Boil some potato's unit they're soft .( Skin on or off , you just have to take the skins off after cooking ) .
 2- Mash those potato's lightly ( not silky smooth , just light mash , it should be easy cuz they're boiled ) 
3 - Now put some oil into a pan , after it heats up , add some garlic and onion until light brown . Then add your mashed potatoes in and add spices ( tumeric powder , coriander powder , chilli powder , garlic power and salt to your liking ) .
4- Mix everything thoroughly , if it sticks put a spoon or two water in it.
5- After 1-2 min cut off the heat cuz potato's are already cooked and enjoy with rice or whatever you like . 

Enjoy

author: @denmark23

text:
as a college student myself, some of my favorite super super cheap parts include:
- dried beans go a long way. way longer than i expect them to. tofu's another protein source that's pretty cheap in my town!
- i substitute chicken stock, which i don't have storage for, with a dash of msg in the water from a can of corn. canned corn always has sweet water which is very useful as a 2-in-1 spice and food!
- the larger the quantity you buy your rice in, the better
- canned tomatoes (especially the stewed ones of any store brand) are basically 50% of a soup. usually half an onion, a bit of garlic, and two cans of tomatoes are literally all i need to make a meal. then just throw in whatever you want to eat in that sauce-- spinach, beans, tofu, the possibilities are endless. this generally functions as 1 meal for 2 people or 2 meals for 1
- potatoes are super cheap and keep well on the shelf so i eat tons of them. mashed or diced and thrown into a soup are my favorite
- eggs are another great protein if you can afford to splurge; i have them on hand because i like making crepes and fried egg sandwiches in my pressure cooker but im aware theyre really expensive rn. theyre excellent with rice or ramen noodles.

generally i just cook a ton of soup for myself because i have a pressure cooker (instant pots are genuinely so good. i dont have a stove, or an oven. an instant pot is an entire kitchen.) soups pretty forgiving and mostly an idle task, especially with a pressure cooker where boiling over isnt a concern.
mashed potatoes are also really easy as a quick calorie source. with practice, i can whip up a batch from raw potatoes in the cupboard in 10 minutes-- i'm not a fast chef. you don't have to peel the potatoes to make the mashed potatoes, and if you drain the water from boiling them (and they're not heavily dirty) you don't have to wash them, either. just make sure to poke holes in the skin so they cook faster.

my weekly budget is around $30 and i shop at trader joes, which isn't the cheapest option around. not quite the $20 a week for 2 people you require but it's pretty close.
author: @ClariseTG

text: Also, food pantries and churches give away weeks worth of food. They'll give away rice, pasta, beans, ramen, things of that sort. I've never seen one give away meat, so you could use EBT to stock up on meat and rely on food banks/churches for sides.

text: A wok is a great cooking vessel, but to really get the most out of one, you need a proper wok burner. If you don't have a jet afterburner built into your kitchen, you are better off using a regular pan. Western stoves don't have burners that can get hot enough for traditional wok cooking. They, of course, also can't hold the round bottom of a wok and any wok that has a flat bottom is just a pan with really tall sides.

text:
¬†@DenaInWyo¬† I also got weirdly annoyed at the popcorn because that technique just literally doesn't work on the stoves 90+% of apartments have. Which to be fair I guess 2/3 of these apartments had gas stoves somehow (?????), but still. That's a huge anomaly. At least here, the nicest stove you can get in an apartment is a low end induction burner, and you are paying 50% more than the basic apartment before you're starting to see that. I also have trouble believing that he actually saw a mortar and pestle in any of those 3 apartments, and I'd be more surprised if he saw one big enough to make an appreciable amount of hummus in them.

Some of these are also kind of painfully "chefy". Not in a way that's hard to do, that pan sauce is the hardest thing in the video which a fair mark imo, but in a...why would you ever bother for a personal meal sense. text: Gordon ramsey says not to season your eggs and he claims it makes them "dry". Fun fact, Salt denatures the proteins in the egg (depending on amount ofc) which would make the proteins less capable of contracting when denaturing from the heat. This would make them expel less water, going completely against Mr Ramseys deranged rambling. We did do an experiment with this in a food science course, long story short: Seasoning eggs with a regular amount of salt up to 30 minutes before did nothing to change the amount of water retained by the egg.

text:
Possible improvement on Joshua's desert!!   MAKE IT AN ICE BOX PIE!

In a Bowl:
- 1 can of sweetened condensed milk
- 1 can of Lemonade CONCENTRATE (ask your grocer, it's in the freezer section)
- Shave your strawberries in (Joshua, if they're frozen, can't you just blend them if you have a blender?)
- 1 tub of whipped cream  (you know the kind that comes in a tub? I'm not naming names here)
--------------
- Fold all of that together, then pour into one of those ready-made gram cracker pie crusts (also at your grocer for cheap).  This is enough to pour into two of the gram cracker crusts my store had.
- leave it in your freezer overnight.. NO BAKE!!

Enjoy an amazing lemon strawberry ice box pie.

text: college students, i am one and i only have free weekends but i still mostly cook for myself. i like to make stews, they can be frozen and portioned out, and you basically only slice your veggies, maybe brown your meat and then you wait. if you want to be fancier, you can make your own gnocci to go with the stew (made with potatoes/sweet potatoes -  mashed, salted and spiced and with equal amount of flour). i also often make pierogi/gyoza which also can be frozen. for breakfast i just take a tortilla, put some cream cheese on it, some ham and cheese (i sometimes put corn in too) fold that and grill. burritos are an option too, you can do whatever you want with them. my food spendings are very low, they translate to like 20-30 dollars a week (granted i dont live in usa but still, its also considered to be little where i live).

text:
Not even a college student, just a tired dad looking for quicker yet super tasty meals. Really looking forward to making a bunch of these in the coming weeks!!

Pork stirfry, this was insane, so much intense flavor, probably better than 80% of any style of stirfry I've gotten from a Chinese restaurant.

Garlic chili oil noodles: Very intense flavor, very good overall. Make sure to use a full pack of noodles. I used about 3 of the 5 bundles of a 16 Oz pack and the chili oil was extremely spicy/overpowering.

French toast sticks: Absolutely delicious, super easy to make, pepper added into a cinnamon sugar mixture is a MUST for me from now on.

text:
The thing that got me through most of my pre-work life is the simplest thing ever and I could eat buckets of it:
2 med/large potatoes, 2-3 eggs, any neutral tasting frying fat/oil (cheapest kind around my parts), pan with a lid, s&p, dried herbs (italian dried mix works well, if not available: oregano, thyme, basil will work but will change the taste profile as the pretty much only seasoning, so pick your favourite).
Cut potatoes into ~2 mm slices (i can do it over the pan at this point, accurate cuts are not required) and dump them into the pan while it's heating up the oil, spreading them until you cover an entire layer. S&P + herb the whole thing then cut the other potato, layer it on top and S&P + H again. Cover with lid. Fry on medium heat untill bottom layer is golden brown. Flip so the top layer can fry too, cover again. As I'm lazy I tend to add eggs right on top of that, so when nearly done, remove cover, crack in the eggs, preferably away from the sides of the pan, salt the yolks a bit for taste, cut the heat entirely and put cover back on - important! don't lift the cover at all, to check the eggs just shake the pan a bit, solid whites won't move around (unless your cover is not see through xD). Wait untill whites are solid but yolks are still liquid. Serve in a bowl rather than a plate, remembering to burst the yolks, since they will cook in the residual heat of the potatoes.
It sounds silly, but somehow it's more than just the sum of the parts. And it's cheap as f%^&. You need only a pan and a heat source. The only struggle you can have with this recipe is heat control. Some pans conduct heat better, some heating options do as well. If your potatoes are browning but they are still raw in the middle - your heat is too high. If they are wilting and not browning - the heat is too low. That's it.
Options - it goes surprisingly well with garlic mayo based sauce. You can add cheese on top after turning and before adding eggs. Onions added before cheese would work too. Any leftover sausage can be cubed and thrown on top of 2nd layer right at the start to heat up and get crispy after turning. Raw meats should rather be prepped separately and added to the bowl.
As I'm now a responsible working adult, I tend not to eat this often, cause it's anything but healthy. I got time and means to make "better" things, But I'm pretty sure I made and ate hundreds of kilos of this thing in my younger days.

text: 24 mini corn dogs = $1.81.  5 cheapo franks cut into 5 pieces each, 1 egg, half cup each of cornmeal and flour, 1/2 C sugar (could be less and healthier), 1/2 C water, 1/4 C melted butter, pinch baking soda and dash of salt.  Put one frank piece into each sprayed mini muffin pan cup and spoon in batter.  Bake at 375 for 10 minutes.  Any excess batter can be baked or quickly skillet fried and maybe add bits of cheese or leftovers but don't toss perfectly good food.  We just had these for dinner and couldn't be easier.

text:
The best tip to healthy meals - buy fresh vegetables.
Preferebly those in Season (tastier and cheaper) and those that can go with a lot of combinations.

So for example: Zucchini, leeks, carrots, mushrooms, Kohlrabi, Broccoli...
Frozen: Spinach, Peas, Cauliflower

Tomatoes and Cucumber for snacking.

With some other cheap staples - potatoes and onions - and some dried goods (like  rice, noodles and chickpeas) you'll have lots of options.

text: Genuinely: when all I had was a microwave, I cooked a lot of microwave potatoes and sweet potatoes. It's a tasty meal and also very cheap. Poke the potato with a fork or (carefully) with a knife, microwave a minute at a time until soft and luxurious, top with cheese, butter, bacon bits, microwave another 20-30 seconds until butter and cheese is melty, add sour cream. A balanced meal.
